Abstract¶

The Waleffe-Kim-Hamilton model of transition and sustained turbulence is simulated and used to generate experimental data. The data then has noise added to it and is plugged into the Sparse Identification of Nonlinear Dynamics (SINDy) algorithm to generate an experimental model of the WKH system. The SINDy algorithm was found to be robust in its ability to recreate the WKH system given varying parameter sets and noise levels.

Introduction¶

The goal of this project is to properly use an algorithm for the Sparse Identification of Nonlinear Dynamics (SINDy) to identify nonlinear differential equations from the Waleffe-Kim-Hamilton (WKH) model of transition and sustained turbulence. The WKH model used in this project is defined by the following equations found from [1] Kalur2020(p. 3),

$$ \begin{bmatrix} \dot{u} \\ \dot{v} \\ \dot{w} \\ \dot{m} \\ \end{bmatrix} \quad = \quad \begin{bmatrix} -\dfrac{\lambda}{Re} & 1 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & -\dfrac{\mu}{Re} & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & -\dfrac{\nu}{Re} & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0 & -\dfrac{\sigma}{Re} \\ \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} u \\ v \\ w \\ m \\ \end{bmatrix} \quad + \quad \begin{bmatrix} 0 & 0 & -\gamma w & v \\ 0 & 0 & \delta w & 0 \\ \gamma w & -\delta w & 0 & 0 \\ -v & 0 & 0 & 0 \\ \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} u \\ v \\ w \\ m \\ \end{bmatrix} \tag{1} $$

Equation $(1)$ can be succinctly represented in the form,

$$\dot{x} = Ax + Q(x)x \tag{2} $$

In the state vector $x$ from $(2)$, $u$ is the amplitude of the spanwise modulation of streamwise velocity, $v$ is the amplitude of streamwise rolls, $w$ is the amplitude of the inflection streak instability and $m$ is the amplitude of the mean shear. These will be the fundamental variables monitored in the analysis of the WHK model. In the A matrix of $(2)$ the constants $\lambda$, $\mu$, $\nu$, $\sigma$, correspond to positive viscous decay rates. $Re$ is the Reynolds number. The $Q(x)$ contains the constants $\gamma$ and $\delta$ which are nonlinear interaction coefficients of equal sign.

To recreate the WKH model from simulated experimental data the SINDy function will be used. This algorithm will be of the form found in [2] Data-Driven Science and Engineering(p. 289),

$$\dot{x} = \Theta (x) \Xi \tag{3} $$

Where $\Theta (X)$ is a library of possible nonlinear functions and the columns of matrix $\Xi$ are the vectors of active coefficients. The determination of the coefficients should allow for the reconstruction of the original dynamical system based solely off of the simulated experimental data. In Figure (1) the SINDy algorithm is visualized for the Lorenz System for greater clarity.

Figure (1). Schematic of SINDy algorithm. [2] Data-Driven Science and Engineering(p. 290)

Methods¶

To begin the WKH model's equations as described in Eq $(1)$ are written into a function for use in simulating the system throughout the process. Using built in Python integration functions the WKH system is integrated to get values for the four major variables $u$, $v$, $w$ and $m$ over time. The derivative of these variables over time is then generated for use in the SINDy algorithm's functions. The relevant pieces of the simulated WKH model is then plugged into the SINDy algorithm. These functions are slightly modified versions of the functions found in [3] SINDY_Lorenz code provided by [2] Data-Driven Science and Engineering. From SINDy the matrix $\Xi$ as described in Eq $(3)$ is found and used to reconstruct an experimental version of the dynamical system $\dot{x}$. Specifically the viscous decay rates and nonlinear constants from Eq $(1)$ are determined algebraically from the experimental system. Both the theoretical and experimental systems are plotted for visual comparison. For quantitative analysis the mean difference of the theoretical and experimental systems are found for all four variables as well as the standard deviation of those differences. With this workflow in place, noise is then added to the simulated system seen by the SINDy algorithm to further test the robustness of the approach. The code is then iterated a preferred number of times with increasing noise value for further boundary testing.

## Simulate the Waleffe-Kim-Hamilton Model
t = np.linspace(0,10,1000)

lam = 10
mu = 10
nu = 15
sigma = 10
Re = 10000
gamma = 0.1
delta = 1

def WKH_deriv(uvwm, t, lam=lam, mu=mu, nu=nu, sigma=sigma, Re=Re, gamma=gamma, delta=delta):

    u = uvwm[0]
    v = uvwm[1]
    w = uvwm[2]
    m = uvwm[3]

    dudt = -(lam/Re)*u+v-gamma*(w**2)+v*m
    dvdt = -(mu/Re)*v+delta*(w**2)
    dwdt = -(nu/Re)*w+gamma*w*u-delta*w*v
    dmdt = -(sigma/Re)*m-v*u

    return np.array([dudt, dvdt, dwdt, dmdt])

x0 = np.array([0, 0, 0, 0]) #!!!!!!!!!!!!Tetsing at initial values of 0!!!!!!
X = integrate.odeint(WKH_deriv, x0, t)
utheo = X[:, 0]
vtheo = X[:, 1]
wtheo = X[:, 2]
mtheo = X[:, 3]

#plot the four variables
plt.plot(t, utheo, label="u")
plt.plot(t, vtheo, label="v")
plt.plot(t, wtheo, label="w")
plt.plot(t, mtheo, label="m")

plt.title("X Variables Values Over Time Initial Condition of 0")
plt.ylabel('Variables Values')
plt.xlabel('Time [s]')
plt.legend(loc="upper right")
plt.show()

Results and Analysis¶

To test the accuracy of the WKH system function, the above code simulates the system with initial values of 0 for all four variables found in $x$. According to [2] Data-Driven Science and Engineering these values should correspond to the systems equilibrium point. The expected result for an accurate WKH model is for all variables to return a value of 0. As seen in the above figure this is true for our model, confirming its accuracy.

#Define mean array function
def meanarray(array):
    mean = sum(array)/len(array)
    return mean

#Define standard deviation of array function
def sdarray(array):
    sd = 0
    inside = 0

    mean = sum(array)/len(array)

    i = 0
    for i in range(len(array)):
        inside = inside + ((array[i] - mean)**2)
        i = i + 1

    sd = math.sqrt(inside/len(array))
    return sd

#Define clean up near zero values in an array function
def cleanzeros(array, threshold):
        cleanarray = np.zeros_like(array)
        j = 0
        i = 0
        for i in range(len(array)):
            if abs(array[i]) <= threshold:
                cleanarray[i] = 0
            else:
                cleanarray[i] = array[i]

            i = i + 1

        return cleanarray
    
#Define percent error of an array function   
def percenterror(theory, experimental):
    perror = np.zeros_like(theory)
    i = 0
    for i in range(len(theory)):
        perror[i, 0] = abs((experimental[i] - theory[i, 0])/theory[i, 0])*100

    i = i + 1
    return perror

#Define difference of two arrays function   
def diff(theory, experimental):
    diff = np.zeros_like(theory)
    i = 0
    for i in range(len(theory)):
        diff[i, 0] = abs(experimental[i] - theory[i, 0])

    i = i + 1
    return diff

            dx[j,:] = WKH_deriv(X[j,:],0)



        ## SINDy Function Definitions
        def poolData(yin,nVars,polyorder):
            n = yin.shape[0]
            yout = np.zeros((n,1))

            # poly order 0
            yout[:,0] = np.ones(n)

            # poly order 1
            for i in range(nVars):
                yout = np.append(yout,yin[:,i].reshape((yin.shape[0],1)),axis=1)

            # poly order 2
            if polyorder >= 2:
                for i in range(nVars):
                    for j in range(i,nVars):
                        yout = np.append(yout,(yin[:,i]*yin[:,j]).reshape((yin.shape[0],1)),axis=1)

            # poly order 3
            if polyorder >= 3:
                for i in range(nVars):
                    for j in range(i,nVars):
                        for k in range(j,nVars):
                            yout = np.append(yout,(yin[:,i]*yin[:,j]*yin[:,k]).reshape((yin.shape[0],1)),axis=1)

            return yout

        def sparsifyDynamics(Theta,dXdt,lamb,n):
            Xi = np.linalg.lstsq(Theta,dXdt,rcond=None)[0] # Initial guess: Least-squares

            for k in range(10):
                smallinds = np.abs(Xi) < lamb # Find small coefficients
                Xi[smallinds] = 0                          # and threshold
                for ind in range(n):                       # n is state dimension
                    biginds = smallinds[:,ind] == 0
                    # Regress dynamics onto remaining terms to find sparse Xi
                    Xi[biginds,ind] = np.linalg.lstsq(Theta[:,biginds],dXdt[:,ind],rcond=None)[0]

            return Xi



        ## Find Constants with SINDy
        n = 4 # number of variables- 4 for u v w m.

        Theta = poolData(X,n,3) # Up to third order polynomials
        lamb = 0.025 # 0.025 # sparsification knob lambda
        Xi = sparsifyDynamics(Theta,dx,lamb,n)

        #print results
        A = np.array([[-(lam/Re), 1, 0, 0], 
                      [0, -(mu/Re), 0, 0],
                      [0, 0, -(nu/Re), 0],

        Q = np.array([[0, 0, -(gamma), 1], 
                      [0, 0, delta, 0],
                      [gamma, -(delta), 0, 0],
                      [-1, 0, 0, 0]])

                    i = i + 1

                    i = i + 1

                    dmdtE = dmdtE + (Xi[i, j])*ordername[0, i]
                    i = i + 1

                    i = i + 1

Results and Analysis Cont.¶

Parameter Set lambda mu nu sigma delta gamma
W 10 10 15 10 1 0.1
Table (1). Parameter Sets from [1] Kalur2020.pdf page (p. 4)

The code is designed to allow for the iteration of multiple parameter sets, each at increasing levels of noise according to the number of desired iterations. In this analysis four parameter sets have been chosen. The first is the parameter set found in Table (1). This set will be used as the basis for our analysis. In the first parameter set a low Reynold's Number of 1000 is used. The second set's Reynold's Number is increased to 10000. In the third set the viscous decay rates are all increased heavily. And for the fourth set the nonlinear interaction coefficients are increased instead. For each of these parameter sets noise is added to each additional iteration with the first experimental model given no noise. The standard deviation of the noise is listed before the experimental dynamical system's plot for each iteration.

For all four parameter sets at zero noise the SINDy function is able to recreate the system with negligible error. This is similar to the previous test for the WKH model and confirms the basic validity of the code. As the noise increases with each iteration so does the difference found between the theoretical and experimental systems. For the first three sets SINDy is able to recreate the systems while keeping with the general behavior up until about one standard deviation in the noise function. Interestingly, for all noise values of parameter sets 1, 2 and 4 the equations generated treat the constants $\lambda$, $\mu$, $\nu$, $\sigma$ as though they are zero and compensate with other terms in the SINDy equations. This does not seem to affect the general accuracy of the experimental system when compared to parameter set 3 which properly predicts the viscous decay rates as shown in the results window above. This is likely due to the fact that the coefficients for $x$ variables are the viscous decay rates divided by the Reynold's Number. Due to the Reynold's Number being much larger than the given viscous decay rates the coefficients will be very small and may then be less likely to be identified as fundamental components through SINDy. Parameter set 3 has a much larger set of viscous decay rates which would increase the size of the coefficients which may explain why the constants are then correctly identified. Finally for parameter set 4 the only major error by SINDy in this analysis is found. When the nonlinear interaction coefficients were increased, and noise was added the SINDy functions prediction for $w$ suffered. The error for $w$ spiked heavily when compared to the other variables in the same trial. A possible explanation is that the $w$ is marginally more sensitive to the nonlinear interaction coefficients.

Discussion and Conclusions¶

Overall, the SINDy algorithm has been shown to successfully recreate the WKH system with varying parameter sets and noise levels. For the scale of tests done over the course of this project the SINDy function seems to be very robust and only had a meaningful error in one parameter set under strange conditions. With further testing these results could be further improved. More extensive testing could be carried out using this code with more extreme examples of the WKH system. The SINDy function could be improved with the use of more efficient numerical derivative methods geared toward use with SINDy. I feel that the experimental system could be further improved with the additional use of traditional data methods such as smoothing and interpolation to clean up the noisier results.
